          "body": "Verse 8 reintroduces Stephen, now described with two new modifiers of *pleres*: *grace* (*charis*) and *power* (*dunamis*). Same root as the apostolic descriptions (4:33; 5:12) — Stephen's ministry now mirrors theirs in wonders and signs (*teras kai semeion*, the same pairing as 2:22; 5:12). The Seven were not deacons in some lower sense; they were Spirit-filled ministers whose service of tables freed them, paradoxically, for Spirit-filled public witness. Stephen's wisdom and Spirit (6:10) recall Jesus's promise in Luke 21:15 — *I will give you utterance and wisdom which none of your opponents will be able to resist or refute*. The promise was given to all the disciples; Stephen is its first major fulfillment. When his opponents from the Synagogue of the Freedmen — likely including Saul of Tarsus (cf. 7:58; 22:3) — cannot defeat him in open debate, they resort to the same machinery used against Jesus: suborned witnesses (6:11), inflamed mob (6:12), Sanhedrin trial (6:12, 15), false charges about destroying the Temple and changing Moses's customs (6:13-14, cf. Mark 14:58)."
