          "title": "A face like the face of an angel — heaven's verdict",
          "body": "The chapter closes on an arresting image. The Council fixes its gaze on Stephen (*atenizo* — to stare intently, sustained looking) and sees his face *like the face of an angel* (6:15). Luke does not explain it. The allusion is to Moses, whose face shone after meeting with God on Sinai (Exodus 34:29-35) — the same Moses Stephen is accused of blaspheming. The irony is sharp: the accused, charged with rejecting Moses, bears the very mark Moses bore. And it is the *Council itself* — Stephen's prosecutors — that registers the divine endorsement. They see what they do not want to see. The chapter ends suspended on this image, leaving the reader to hear Stephen's speech in chapter 7 from a man whose face heaven has already vindicated. The crown (*stephanos*) is already visible before the stoning begins."
